description:
Refers to variables that can be used in configuration script, having integer or string value.
This kind of variables are faster than AVPs, being referenced directly to memory location.
The value of the AVP identified by 'id'.
Represents the value of N-th AVP identified by 'id'.

Pseudo[The list of pseudo-variables]


$$ - represents the character '$'

URI inP[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ai - reference to URI in request's P-Asserted-Identity header (see RFC 3325)

Auth Digest URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$adu - URI from Authorization or Proxy-Authorization header. This URI is used when calculating the HTTP Digest Response.

Auth algorithm[The list of pseudo-variables]


$aa - algorithm from Authorization or Proxy-Authorization header.

Auth realm[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ar - realm from Authorization or Proxy-Authorization header

Auth username user[The list of pseudo-variables]


$au - user part of username from Authorization or Proxy-Authorization header

Auth username domain[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ad - domain part of username from Authorization or Proxy-Authorization header

Auth whole username[The list of pseudo-variables]


$aU - whole username from Authorization or Proxy-Authorization header

Acc username[The list of pseudo-variables]


$Au - username for accounting purposes. It's a selective pseudo variable (inherited from acc module). It returns auth username ($au) if exists or From username ($fU) otherwise.

Request's first branch[The list of pseudo-variables]


$br - reference to request's first branch


It is R/W variable, you can assign values to it directly in configuration file (will add a new branch).

Request's all branches[The list of pseudo-variables]


$bR - reference to request's all branches

Branch flags[The list of pseudo-variables]


$bf - reference to branch flags of branch 0 (RURI) - decimal output


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)

Branch flags[The list of pseudo-variables]


$bF - reference to branch flags of branch 0 (RURI) - hexa output


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)

Body size[The list of pseudo-variables]


$bs - body size

Call[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ci - reference to body of call-id header

Content[The list of pseudo-variables]


$cl - reference to body of content-length header

TCP Connection ID[The list of pseudo-variables]


$conid - The TCP connection ID of the connection the current message arrived on for TCP, TLS, WS, and WSS.  Set to $null for SCTP and UDP.

CSeq Number[The list of pseudo-variables]


$cs - reference to the sequence number in the CSeq header. The method in the CSeq header is identical to the request method, thus use $rm to get the method (works also for responses).

CSeq Header Body[The list of pseudo-variables]


$csb - reference to the CSeq header body (number method).

Contact header[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ct - reference to body of contact header

Content[The list of pseudo-variables]


$cT - reference to body of content-type header

Domain of destination URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$dd - reference to domain of destination uri (without port)

Diversion header URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$di - reference to Diversion header URI

Diversion "privacy" parameter[The list of pseudo-variables]


$dip - reference to Diversion header “privacy” parameter value

Diversion "reason" parameter[The list of pseudo-variables]


$dir - reference to Diversion header “reason” parameter value

Diversion "counter" parameter[The list of pseudo-variables]


$dic - reference to Diversion header “counter” parameter value

Port of destination URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$dp - reference to port of destination uri

Transport protocol of destination URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$dP - reference to transport protocol of destination uri

Destination set[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ds - reference to destination set

Destination URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$du - reference to destination uri


If loose_route() returns TRUE a destination uri is set according to the first Route header.
$du is also set if lookup() function of 'registrar' module finds contact(s) behind NAT. You can
set $du to any SIP URI.

 sip:kamailio.org
 sip:pbx123.kamailio.org;transport=udp
 sip:[2001:DB8::33:2]:5980;transport=tls

It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)


To reset $du:

$du = $null;

From URI domain[The list of pseudo-variables]


$fd - reference to domain in URI of 'From' header

From display name[The list of pseudo-variables]


$fn - reference to display name of 'From' header

Forced socket[The list of pseudo-variables]


$fs - reference to the forced socket for message sending (if any) in the form proto:ip:port


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file). Transport proto can be omitted when assigning value, in which case it is taken from destination URI of the message.

From tag[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ft - reference to tag parameter of 'From' header

Initial From tag[The list of pseudo-variables]


$fti - reference to tag parameter of 'From' header as it was in the initial request (e.g., initial INVITE).


The value From tag in the initial request can be in the To tag, if the request within the dialog is sent by the callee. This variable detect who sent the request within the dialog and returns the proper value that was in the From tag of the request initiating the dialog.


It is exported by rr module and has to be used after loose_route(). The append_fromtag parameter is required to be set to 1 in order to have this variable returning the right value.

From URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$fu - reference to URI of 'From' header


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)


Note that changing the From: header may break backwards compatibility with SIP 1.0 devices.

From URI username[The list of pseudo-variables]


$fU - reference to username in URI of 'From' header


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)


Note that changing the From: header may break backwards compatibility with SIP 1.0 devices.

SIP message buffer[The list of pseudo-variables]


$mb - reference to SIP message buffer

Flags[The list of pseudo-variables]


$mf - reference to message/transaction flags set for current SIP request


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)

Flags in hexadecimal[The list of pseudo-variables]


$mF -reference to message/transaction flags set for current SIP request in hexa-decimal


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)

SIP message id[The list of pseudo-variables]


$mi - reference to SIP message id

SIP message length[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ml - reference to SIP message length

SIP Message Type[The list of pseudo-variables]


$mt - returns 1 if the sip message is a request, returns 2 if the sip message is a reply

Domain original R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$od - reference to domain in request's original R-URI

Port in original R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$op - reference to port of original R-URI

Protocol of original R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$oP - reference to transport protocol of original R-URI

Original R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ou - reference to request's original URI

Username in original R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$oU - reference to username in request's original URI

Domain in P[The list of pseudo-variables]


$pd - reference to domain in request's P-Preferred-Identity header URI (see RFC 3325)

Display Name in P[The list of pseudo-variables]


$pn - reference to Display Name in request's P-Preferred-Identity header (see RFC 3325)

Process id[The list of pseudo-variables]


$pp - reference to process id (pid)

Protocol of received message[The list of pseudo-variables]


$pr or $proto - protocol of received message (udp, tcp, tls, sctp, ws, wss)

protocol id[The list of pseudo-variables]


$prid - internal protocol id


 0 - NONE

 1 - UDP

 2 - TCP

 3 - TLS

 4 - SCTP

 5 - WS

 6 - WSS

 7 - OTHER

User in P[The list of pseudo-variables]


$pU - reference to user in request's P-Preferred-Identity header URI (see RFC 3325)

URI in P[The list of pseudo-variables]


$pu - reference to URI in request's P-Preferred-Identity header (see RFC 3325)

Body of request/reply[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rb - reference to message body

Returned code[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rc - reference to returned code by last invoked function


$retcode - same as $rc

Domain in R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rd - reference to domain in request's URI (without port) or to the Namespace Specific String of a URN (see RFC 2141)


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)

Request Direction[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rdir(key) - get the direction of the request within dialog.


The direction is 'downstream' if sent by the caller and 'upstream' if sent by callee.


The key can be:


 id - the returned value is an integer: 1 - for direction downstream, 2 - for direction upstream

 name - the returned value is a string: 'downstream' or 'upstream'



Example:

if($rdir(name)=="upstream") {
  xlog("request was sent by callee\n");
}

The variable is exported by rr module and append_fromtag parameter must be enabled. The variable has to be used after loose_route() function.

Remote[The list of pseudo-variables]


$re - reference to Remote-Party-ID header URI

SIP method[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rm - reference to request's method. Works also for replies (by using the CSeq header)

SIP Method ID[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rmid - returns internal integer representation of SIP method type

URI in first Route header[The list of pseudo-variables]


$route_uri - returns the string with URI field in the first Route header

Port in R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rp - reference to port of R-URI


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)

Protocol of R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rP - reference to transport protocol of R-URI

SIP reply reason phrase[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rr - reference to reply's reason phrase (the text after reply code)

SIP reply code[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rs - reference to reply's status (status-code, response-code, reply-code)

Refer[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rt - reference to URI of refer-to header

Request URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ru - reference to request's URI (address in the first line of a SIP request)


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)

Username in R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rU - reference to username in request's URI or to the Namespace Identifier of a URN (see RFC 2141)


It is R/W variable (you can assign values to it directly in configuration file)

SIP message version[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rv - reference to SIP message (reply or request) version

Record internal Unique ID[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ruid - the Record internal Unique ID for the location record selected by calling registrar:lookup()

URI Scheme of R[The list of pseudo-variables]


$rz - returns R-URI scheme, possible values: sip, sips, tel, tels and urn, R-URI scheme parsing error should be reflected by value: none

Received advertised IP address[The list of pseudo-variables]


$RAi - reference to advertised IP address of the interface where the request has been received, or $Ri if no advertised address.

Received advertised port[The list of pseudo-variables]


$RAp - reference to advertised port where the request has been received, or $Rp if no advertised port.

Received IP address[The list of pseudo-variables]


$Ri - reference to IP address of the interface where the request has been received

Received port[The list of pseudo-variables]


$Rp - reference to the port where the message was received

Advertised socket URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$RAu - local socket where the SIP messages was received in URI format, without transport parameter for UDP, using advertised address when available.

Advertised socket URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$RAut - local socket where the SIP messages was received in URI format, always with transport parameter, using advertised address when available.

Received socket URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$Ru - local socket where the SIP messages was received in URI format, without transport parameter for UDP.

Received socket URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$Rut - local socket where the SIP messages was received in URI format, always with transport parameter.

Script flags[The list of pseudo-variables]


$sf - reference to script flags - decimal output

Script flags[The list of pseudo-variables]


$sF - reference to script flags - hexa output

Source IP address[The list of pseudo-variables]


$si - reference to IP source address of the message - see also $siz

Source IP address[The list of pseudo-variables]


$siz - reference to IP source address of the message, with enclosing square brackets for IPv6

Source port[The list of pseudo-variables]


$sp - reference to the source port of the message

Statistics[The list of pseudo-variables]


$stat(name) - return the value of statistic item specified by 'name'

Source address as URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$su - returns the representation of source address (ip, port, proto) as SIP URI. If the proto is UDP, then it is not added (being the default transport protocol).


Its value looks like:

"sip:ip:port" -- if proto is UDP
"sip:ip:port;transport=proto"  -- if proto is not UDP

Note that WS and WSS are both represented by transport=ws, conforming with the IETF RFC for SIP over WebSocket.

Source address as full URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$sut - returns the representation of source address (ip, port, proto) as full SIP URI. The proto UDP is added also as transport parameter.


Its value looks like:

"sip:ip:port;transport=proto"

To URI Domain[The list of pseudo-variables]


$td - reference to domain in URI of 'To' header

To display name[The list of pseudo-variables]


$tn - reference to display name of 'To' header

To tag[The list of pseudo-variables]


$tt - reference to tag parameter of 'To' header

Initial To tag[The list of pseudo-variables]


$tti - reference to tag parameter of 'To' header as it was in the SIP response to the initial request (e.g., 200ok to the initial INVITE).


The value To tag in the initial transaction can be in the From tag, if the request within the dialog is sent by the callee. This variable detect who sent the request within the dialog and returns the proper value that was in the To tag of the transaction initiating the dialog.


It is exported by rr module and has to be used after loose_route(). The append_fromtag parameter is required to be set to 1 in order to have this variable returning the right value.

To URI[The list of pseudo-variables]


$tu - reference to URI of 'To' header

To URI Username[The list of pseudo-variables]


$tU - reference to username in URI of 'To' header

Startup timestamp[The list of pseudo-variables]


$Tb - reference to unix timestamp of the time at which kamailio was started (boot time)

String formatted time [The list of pseudo-variables]


$Tf - reference string formatted time


Note: the system time is retrieved only once for each processed SIP message. Subsequent calls of $Tf for same SIP message will return same value.

String formatted time [The list of pseudo-variables]


$TF - reference string formatted time


Note: the system time is computed for each call of $TF. Subsequent calls of $TF for same SIP message may return different values.

Unix time stamp [The list of pseudo-variables]


$Ts - reference to unix time stamp


Note: the system time is retrieved only once for each processed SIP message. Subsequent calls of $Ts for same SIP message will return same value.

Unix time stamp [The list of pseudo-variables]


$TS - reference to unix time stamp


Note: the system time is computed for each call of $TS. Subsequent calls of $TS for same SIP message may return different values.

User agent header[The list of pseudo-variables]


$ua - reference to user agent header field

version[The list of pseudo-variables]


$version(num) - version as number


$version(full) - full version string “name version architecture/platform”


$version(hash) - TBA

$sndfrom(name)[Send Address Attributes]


$snd(name) - return attributes of the address from where the request is going to be sent (local socket).


$sndfrom(name) - return attributes of the address from where the request is going to be sent (local socket, same as $snd(name)).


The name can have same values as for $sndto(…).

$sndto(name)[Send Address Attributes]


$sndto(name) - return attributes of the address to where the request is going to be sent (remote socket).


They are available in onsend_route. The name can be:


 ip - IP address of destination

 af - address family to be used to send (numeric)

 port - port of destination address

 proto - transport protocol to be used to send (numeric)

 sproto - transport protocol to be used to send (string)

 buf - entire send buffer as string

 len - length of outgoing packet (length of above buf)



Example:

onsend_route {
if($snd(ip)==10.10.10.10)
{
    ...
  }
}

$BM_time_diff[Benchmark module Pseudo-Variables]


$BM_time_diff - the time difference elapsed between calls of bm_start_timer(name) and bm_log_timer(name). The value is 0 if no bm_log_timer() was called.

$dlg(attr)[Dialog module Pseudo-Variables]


Return the attribute of the current processed dialog.


It is R/O variable.


The 'attr' can be:


 h_id - hash id

 h_entry - hash entry

 ref - reference count

 state - state of dialog

 to_rs - To route set

 from_rs - From route set

 dflags - dialog internal flags

 sflags - dialog script flags

 callid - sip call id

 to_uri - To uri

 to_tag - To tag

 from_uri - From uri

 from_tag - From tag

 toroute - timeout route

 lifetime - timeout inteval

 start_ts - start timestamp

 to_cseq - To CSeq

 from_cseq - From CSeq

 to_contact - To contact address

 from_contact - From contact address

 to_bindaddr - To bind address

 from_bindaddr - From bind address

$dlg_ctx(attr)[Dialog module Pseudo-Variables]


Return the attribute of the context for current processed dialog.


Some of the attributes are R/W variables.


The 'attr' can be:


 set - returns 1 if the dialog for current context is set, 0 otherwise

 flags - get/set dialog flags

 timeout_route - get/set route name to be executed on timeout

 timeout_route_id - get internal id for the route to be executed on timeout

 timeout_bye - set to 1 if BYE has to be sent when dialog lifetime elapses

 timeout - set the dialog lifetime (in seconds)

 on - get/set an integer value associated with the context (cfg usage)

 dir - get direction of the request for the dialog of the current context (0 - unknown, 1 - downstream, 2 - upstream)

$dlg_var(key)[Dialog module Pseudo-Variables]


Store and retrieve custom variable for current processed dialog.


It is R/W variable.


The 'key' can be any string.

variable attributes[Erlang module Pseudo-Variables]


* type - get variable type. Possible types are: atom, integer, list, string, tuple, pid and ref.


* length - get length of list or tuple.


* format - prints a term, in clear text. It tries to resemble the term printing in the Erlang shell.

$erl_atom(name)[Erlang module Pseudo-Variables]


$erl_atom(name) pseudo variable allows create analog to Erlang atom data type.
Erlang atom is a literal, a constant with name. Formatted output pseudo variable
atom could be enclosed in single quotes (') if it does not begin with a 
lower-case letter or if it contains other characters than alphanumeric characters,
underscore (_), or @.


Example:

$erl_atom(A) = node@host.tld;

xlogl(L_DEBUG,$$erl_atom(A): $erl_atom(A=format)\n);

$erl_pid(name)[Erlang module Pseudo-Variables]


Holds Eralng process identifier. Provides access to Erlang PID value and could
be used in send message.

$erl_ref(name)[Erlang module Pseudo-Variables]


Holds Erlang reference. Provides access to reference value and could be used in
send message.

$erl_xbuff(name)[Erlang module Pseudo-Variables]


Generic pseudo variable to acts as other pseudo variables exported from Erlang
module.

$sht(htable=key)[HTable module Pseudo-Variables]


Access hash table entries.


It is R/W variable, you can assign values to it directly in configuration file.  Hash table entry can be deleted by assigning value $null to it.


The “htname” must be a hash table name defined via “htable” parameter.


The “key” can be:


 static string - set of characters without pseudo-variables

 dynamic string - set of characters that include pseudo-variables. The pseudo-variables will be evaluated at runtime.


...
modparam(htable, htable, a=size=4;)
...
$sht(a=$au) = 1;
$sht(a=$ru) = $fu;
...

$shtex(htable=key)[HTable module Pseudo-Variables]


Access hash table entry expire value. Value represents the seconds until the htable entry will expire and be deleted from htable.


It is R/W variable, you can assign values to it directly in configuration file.


The “htname” must be a hash table name defined via “htable” parameter and have auto-expire greater than 0.


The “key” can be:


 static string - set of characters without pseudo-variables

 dynamic string - set of characters that include pseudo-variables. The pseudo-variables will be evaluated at runtime.


...
modparam(htable, htable, a=size=4;autoexpire=120;)
...
$sht(a=$au) = 1;
$shtex(a=$au) = 10;
...

$shtcn(htable=exp)[HTable module Pseudo-Variables]


Count items matching the name by regexp.


The “htname” must be a hash table name defined via “htable” parameter.


The exp can be:


 reqexp - match by regular expression 'regexp'

 ~~regexp - match by regular expression 'regexp'

 ~%prefix - match by right prefix

 %~prefix - match by left prefix

 ==value - match by string value

 eqvalue - match by integer value

 * * - (two asterisks next to each other) - count all items



The exp can contain pseudo-variables.

...
modparam(htable, htable, a=size=4;)
...
$sht(a=abc) = 1;
$shtex(a=ade) = 10;
xlog($shtcn(a=a.*));
...

$shtcv(htable=exp)[HTable module Pseudo-Variables]


Count items matching the value by regexp.


The “htname” must be a hash table name defined via “htable” parameter.


The exp must follow same rules as for $shtcn(…).

...
modparam(htable, htable, a=size=4;)
...
$sht(a=abc) = xyz;
$shtex(a=ade) = xwt;
xlog($shtcv(a=x.*));
...

$shtinc(htable=key)[HTable module Pseudo-Variables]


Atomic increment of the value for the hash table item.

...
modparam(htable, htable, a=size=4;)
...
$sht(a=$au) = 1;
xlog(==== $shtinc(a=$au)\n);
...

$shtdec(htable=key)[HTable module Pseudo-Variables]


Atomic decrement of the value for the hash table item.

...
modparam(htable, htable, a=size=4;)
...
$sht(a=$au) = 1;
xlog(==== $shtdec(a=$au)\n);
...

$shtitkey(iname)[HTable module Pseudo-Variables]


The key at the current position in the iterator.

$mct(key)[Memcached module Pseudo-Variables]


Access hash table entries stored in the memcached server.


It is R/W variable, you can assign values to it directly in configuration file.


The “key” can be:


 static string - set of characters without pseudo-variables

 dynamic string - set of characters that include pseudo-variables. The pseudo-variables will be evaluated at runtime.



When assigning values, the default expiry will be used.

...
$mct($au) = 1;
$mct($ru) = $fu;
$mct(test) = 1;
xlog(stored value is $mct(test));
$mct(test) = null; # delete it
xlog(stored value is $mct(test)); # will return null
...

$mct(key=expiry)[Memcached module Pseudo-Variables]


Using this alternative format, the default expiry may be overidden by including a custom value at time of assignment.

...
$mct(test=30) = 1; # set expire time to 30 seconds
xlog(stored value is $mct(test));
# sleep 30 seconds
xlog(stored value is $mct(test)); # will return null
...

$mcinc(key)[Memcached module Pseudo-Variables]


Do a atomic increment operation on the value stored in memcached. You need to add a value previously.


It is R/W variable, you can assign values to it directly in configuration file.


The “key” can be:


 static string - set of characters without pseudo-variables

 dynamic string - set of characters that include pseudo-variables. The pseudo-variables will be evaluated at runtime.


...
$mct(cnt) = 1;
$mcinc(cnt) = 2; # increment by 2
xlog(counter is now $mct(cnt));
...

$mcdec(key)[Memcached module Pseudo-Variables]


Do a atomic decrement operation on the value stored in memcached. You need to add a value previously.


It is R/W variable, you can assign values to it directly in configuration file.


The “key” can be:


 static string - set of characters without pseudo-variables

 dynamic string - set of characters that include pseudo-variables. The pseudo-variables will be evaluated at runtime.


...
$mct(cnt) = 10;
$mcdec(cnt) = 2; # decrement by 2
xlog(counter is now $mct(cnt));
...

$T_branch_idx[TMX module Pseudo-Variables]


 the index (starting with 1 for the first branch) of the branch for which is executed the branch_route[]. If used outside of branch_route[] block, the value is '0'.

$T_reply_ruid[TMX module Pseudo-Variables]


 the ruid stored in the current branch of the transaction. The ruid is stored in a branch from the details in a contact binding. In a event_route[tm:branch-failure] block, this is the ruid of the branch that sent a failure reply. In a failure_route[] block, this is the ruid of the winning failure response.

$T_reply_code[TMX module Pseudo-Variables]


 the code of the reply, as follows: in request_route will be the last stateful sent reply; in reply_route will be the current processed reply; in failure_route will be the negative winning reply. In case of no-reply or error, '0' value is returned

$T(name)[TMX module Pseudo-Variables]


 pseudo-variable class to access TM attributes



The name can be:


 id_index - return the internal index of current transaction or $null if not transaction is found

 id_label - return the internal label of current transaction or $null if not transaction is found

 id_index_n - return the internal index of current transaction, if no transaction exists yet, create it

 id_label_n - return the internal label of current transaction, if no transaction exists yet, create it

 reply_code - reply code (alias to $T_reply_code)

 reply_reason - reply reason

 reply_last - last received reply code

 branch_index - branch index (alias to $T_branch_idx)

 ruid - return the internal location ruid field for current branch

 reply_type - 1 if it is a local generated reply, 0 - if no reply for transaction or it is a received reply



Note: the pair (id_index,id_label) uniquely identifies a transaction.

$T_branch(name)[TMX module Pseudo-Variables]


 pseudo-variable class to access TM branch attributes



The name can be:


 flags - Flags of the branch. In a event_route[tm:branch-failure] block, this is the flags of the branch that sent a failure reply. In a failure_route[] block, this is the flags of the winning failure response.

 uri - the R-URI of the branch. Can be used in onreply_route[id] - reply route blocks executed by tm module. For other routing blocks handling requests, the R-URI is returned by $ru

$rr_count[Nathelper module Pseudo-Variables]


 Number of Record Routes in received SIP request or reply.

$rr_top_count[Nathelper module Pseudo-Variables]


 If topmost Record Route in received SIP request or reply is a double Record Route, value of $rr_top_count is 2. If it a single Record Route, value of $rr_top_count is 1. If there is no Record Route(s), value of $rr_top_count is 0.

$mqk(q)[MQueue module Pseudo-Variables]


 return the key of fetched item from queue q

$TV(name)[TimeVal]


Seconds and microseconds taken from struct timeval.


 $TV(s) - seconds (cached at first call per sip message)

 $TV(u) - microseconds (cached at first call per sip message)

 $TV(sn) - seconds (not cached)

 $TV(un) - microseconds (not cached)

 $TV(Sn) - string representation seconds.microseconds (not cached)

$nh(key)[Next hop address]


Return attributes of next hop for the SIP request. Address is taken from dst_uri, if set, if not from new r-uri or original r-uri.


 $nh(u) - uri (lower case u)

 $nh(U) - username (upper case u)

 $nh(d) - domain

 $nh(p) - port (lower case p)

 $nh(P) - transport protocol (upper case p)

$gip(pvc=key)[GeoIP module Pseudo-Variables]


Variables exported by GeoIP module, returning geo-location attributes. The attributes are populated upon calling function geoip_match(ipaddr, pvc).


pvc (container id) is second parameter of geoip_match(..) and key can be:


 cc - country code

 tz - time zone

 zip - postal code

 lat - latitude

 lon - longitude

 dma - dma code

 ips - ip start

 ipe - ip end

 city - city

 area - area code

 regc - region

 regn - region name

 metro - metro code

 contc - continent code



You can call several time geoip_match(ipaddr, pvc) with different ip address and containers in your config, to compare, for example, attributes of source and destination of a call.

geoip_match($si, src);
geoip_match($nh(d), dst);
if($gip(src=cc)==$gip(dst=cc))
{
# source and destination from same country
}

$sipt(calling_party_category) / $sipt(cpc) / $sipt_cpc[SIPT module Pseudo-Variables]


Returns the value of the Calling Party Category for the IAM message. Returns -1 if there is a parsing error.

$sipt(calling_party_number.nature_of_address) / $sipt.(calling_party_number.nai) / $sipt_calling_party_nai[SIPT module Pseudo-Variables]


Returns the value of the Nature of Address Indicator of the Calling Party for the IAM message. Returns -1 if there is a parsing error or if the Calling Party Number is not present.


Can return the following values:


 0 Spare

 1 Subscriber Number (national use)

 2 Unknown (national use)

 3 National (significant) number (national use)

 4 International use



Example:

# get the Calling Nai and add country code if national
if($sipt(calling_party_number.nai) == 3)
{
        $fU = 32 + $fU;
}

$sipt(called_party_number.nature_of_address) / $sipt(called_party_number.nai) / $sipt_called_party_nai[SIPT module Pseudo-Variables]


Returns the value of the Nature of Address Indicator of the Called Party for the IAM message. Returns -1 if there is a parsing error.


Can return the following values:


 0 Spare

 1 Subscriber Number (national use)

 2 Unknown (national use)

 3 National (significant) number

 4 International use

 5 Network-specific number (national use)



Example:

# get the Called Nai and add country code if national
if($sipt(called_party_number.nai) == 3)
{
        $rU = 32 + $rU;
}

$sipt(event_info)[SIPT module Pseudo-Variables]


Returns the value  of the Event Info header of the CPG message. Returns -1 if there is a parsing error.


Can return the following values:


 0 Spare

 1 ALERTING

 2 PROGRESS

 3 In-band information or an appropriate pattern is now available

 4 Call forward on busy

 5 Call forward on no reply

 6 Call forward unconditional

$sipt(backward_call_indicator.charge_indicator)[SIPT module Pseudo-Variables]


Returns the value of the charge indication of the backward call
indicator header in the ACM or COT message. Returns -1 if there is a
parsing error


Can return the following values:


 0 no indication

 1 no charge

 2 charge

 3 spare

JSONRPC Reply[JSONRPCS Variables]


This variable gives access to JSONRPC reply after executing jsonrpc_exec(…) in kamailio.cfg.


The key can be:


 code - code for the JSONRPC response

 text - text of the code for the JSONRPC response

 body - the body of the JSONRPC response

Subscription Attributes[Presence Module Pseudo-Variables]


This variable gives access to attributes of the current subscription. The variable has to be used after executing handle_subscription() in order to provide accurate values.


The key can be:


 uri - subscription URI. Useful in particular for subscriptions within the dialog, when the request URI in SUBSCRIBE is the Contact address from the initial subscription.

Registered Contact Attributes[Registrar Module Pseudo-Variables]


Access the attributes of contact addresses stored in 'profile'.


It must be used after a call of “reg_fetch_contacts()”.

HEP Packet Attributes[sipcapture Module Pseudo-Variables]


The key refers to HEP packet header values:


 version - HEP version

 src_ip - source IP address

 dst_ip - destination IP address

 0x000 - HEP attribute 0x000

 0x999 - HEP attribute 0x999
